The ellipses (...) after a menu item is a common accessibility feature for indicating that the operation is not going to be performed instantly when you press the button and that you will see a dialog.

This is a de facto standard used on all operating systems but missing from user interface. Due to this people may transition issues by mistake as is there no visual indication.

We considered adding the ellipses inside the transition name but this is not a good practice because it would require an enormous number of changes, break third party code that is using these transition names and inevitably introduce inconsistencies and other weird behaviours

The only way to address this in a safe way is by exposing the (non)existence of a dialog into the generated menu, probably using a CSS class for this.

Here is once sample menu item:
{noformat}
<li class="toolbar-item">
<a id="action_id_911" class="toolbar-trigger issueaction-workflow-transition" href="/secure/WorkflowUIDispatcher.jspa?id=512901&amp;action=911&amp;atl_token=AXYJ-U5JK-L1J8-MFCP|c5b4769b70902048156d8b326c808214d354458e|lin">
<span class="trigger-label">Closed</span></a></li>
{noformat}

If you would add a class like {{transition-dialog}} to the <span> element, we can use CSS to add the ... inside the span.

{noformat}
span.transition-dialog:after {
content: "…"
}
{noformat}

Please do use the ellipses Unicode character instead of the 3 dots, it does render better, taking less space.

